Card Fraud Detection
  • Back to Home(current)

    • (1) Data Description¶

    We are asked to predict the probability that an online transaction is fraudulent, as denoted by the binary target isFraud. The data is broken into two files identity and transaction, which are joined by TransactionID. Not all transactions have corresponding identity information.

    Categorical Features - Transaction¶

    ProductCD, card1 - card6, addr1, addr2

    P_emaildomain, R_emaildomain, M1 - M9

    Categorical Features - Identity¶

    DeviceType, DeviceInfo, id_12 - id_38

    The TransactionDT feature is a timedelta from a given reference datetime (not an actual timestamp).

    Files¶

    train_{transaction, identity}.csv - the training set

    test_{transaction, identity}.csv - the test set (to predict the isFraud value for these observations)

    sample_submission.csv - a sample submission file in the correct format

    (2) Additional info from Vesta¶

    Transaction Table¶

    TransactionDT: timedelta from a given reference datetime (not an actual timestamp)

    TransactionAMT: transaction payment amount in USD

    ProductCD: product code, the product for each transaction

    card1 - card6: payment card information, such as card type, card category, issue bank, country, etc.

    addr: address of purchaser. addr1 as billing region(billing zip code), addr2 as billing country

    dist: distances between (not limited) billing address, mailing address, zip code, IP address, phone area, etc.

    P_ and (R__) emaildomain: purchaser and recipient email domain

    C1-C14: counting, such as how many addresses are found to be associated with the payment card, etc. The actual meaning is masked.

    D1-D15: timedelta, such as days between previous transaction, etc.

    M1-M9: match, such as names on card and address, etc.

    Vxxx: Vesta engineered rich features, including ranking, counting, and other entity relations.

    Why would a transaction not have a row of identity? - For various technical reasons, it's challenging to collect all identity information at the real-time transactions

    Identity Table¶

    Variables in this table are identity information network connection information (IP, ISP, Proxy, etc) and digital signature (UA/browser/os/version, etc) associated with transactions. They're collected by Vestas fraud protection system and digital security partners. (The field names are masked and pairwise dictionary will not be provided for privacy protection and contract agreement)

    (4) Exploratory Data Analysis¶

    (4.1) Data imbalance

    in anamoly detection cases (fraud detection being the subset), the input data is almost always imbalanced and this can skew the training model behaviour. Depending on the training model we need to either upscale/downscale data records and/or select model that can handle the imbalanced data approriately (e.g XGBoost/LGBM/Autoencoder)

    In [10]:
    fraud_records = df.isFraud[df.isFraud == 1].count()
print (f"training data has {fraud_records} fraud records out of total {df.shape[0]} records i.e. {round(100*fraud_records/df.shape[0],2)}%")

    training data has 20663 fraud records out of total 590540 records i.e. 3.5%

    (4.2) Lets summarize featurewise summary of train and test datasets

    In [11]:
    # Function to get basic details about dataframe features
def dataframe_summary1(df):

    all = df.columns.tolist()
    first_cut = {'feature_name':[],'dtype':[],'unique_values':[], 'records':[],'nulls':[], '%nulls':[],'%not_nulls':[], '%fraud_rows':[], '%fraud_in_nulls':[], '%fraud_in_not_nulls':[]}
    for feature in all:

        first_cut['feature_name'].append(feature)
        first_cut['dtype'].append(df[feature].dtype)
        first_cut['records'].append(df.shape[0])
        first_cut['unique_values'].append(df[feature].nunique(dropna=False))
        first_cut['nulls'].append(df[feature].isnull().sum())
        first_cut['%nulls'].append(100*df[feature].isnull().sum()/df.shape[0])
        first_cut['%not_nulls'].append(100*df[feature].notnull().sum()/df.shape[0])

        first_cut['%fraud_rows'].append(100*df[feature][df.isFraud==1].size/df.shape[0])

        #Fraud distribution in nulls
        nulls = df[feature].isnull().sum()
        not_nulls = df[feature].notnull().sum()
        frauds_in_nulls = df['isFraud'][(df[feature].isnull()) & (df.isFraud==1)].size
        frauds_in_not_nulls = df['isFraud'][(df[feature].notnull()) & (df.isFraud==1)].size

        if nulls != 0:
            first_cut['%fraud_in_not_nulls'].append(100*frauds_in_not_nulls/not_nulls)
        else:
            first_cut['%fraud_in_not_nulls'].append(100)

        if nulls !=0:
            first_cut['%fraud_in_nulls'].append(100*frauds_in_nulls/nulls)
        else:
            first_cut['%fraud_in_nulls'].append(0)
    summary = pd.DataFrame(first_cut)    
    return summary

# Function to get basic details about test dataframe features (this exclude any reference to target parameter)
def dataframe_summary2(df):

    all = df.columns.tolist()
    first_cut = {'feature_name':[],'dtype':[],'unique_values':[], 'records':[],'nulls':[], '%nulls':[],'%not_nulls':[]}
    for feature in all:

        first_cut['feature_name'].append(feature)
        first_cut['dtype'].append(df[feature].dtype)
        first_cut['records'].append(df.shape[0])
        first_cut['unique_values'].append(df[feature].nunique(dropna=False))
        first_cut['nulls'].append(df[feature].isnull().sum())
        first_cut['%nulls'].append(100*df[feature].isnull().sum()/df.shape[0])
        first_cut['%not_nulls'].append(100*df[feature].notnull().sum()/df.shape[0])

        
    summary = pd.DataFrame(first_cut)    
    return summary

    Conclusion: card2-6 values are uniquely related to card1. this info can be used to fill nulls in card2-6 columns.¶

    In [20]:
    #defining a function to fill nulls with column mode using card1 as pivot value
#e.g nulls in card2-6 columns by checking mode of card2-6 columns for specific card1 value(card1 values has no nulls)

def crossfill_mode(df, fill_columns, link_with):
    
    '''
    INPUT:
    df: dataframe where we are filling nulls
    fill_columns: columns of dataframe df, to fill the nulls
    link_with: 'pivot_column used to check mode of columns (we are using 'card1' in this notebook )'
    
    RETURNs:
    df: dataframe after filling in possible nulls
    '''
    
    print(f"Count of total NaN's in selected features before filling:")
    print(df[fill_columns].isnull().sum())

    for feature in fill_columns:
        print(f' filling-in {feature} Nulls')
        df[feature] = df.apply(
            lambda row: df[feature][(df[link_with] == row[link_with])].mode()[0] 
            if ((pd.isnull(row[feature])) and (len(df[feature][(df[link_with] == row[link_with])].mode()) !=0)) else row[feature],axis=1) 
    print(f"Count of NaN's in features after filling:")
    print(df[fill_columns].isnull().sum())
    return df
########################################################################################################
#This function is same as crossfill_mode, but runs faster as a pivot look up table is made beforehand
#but it needs an additional parameter for indexing of pivot table
def crossfill(df, list_index, fill_columns, link_with):
    
    print(f"Count of NaN's in features before filling:")
    print(df[fill_columns].isnull().sum())
    
    temp = df.pivot_table(index =list_index, values = 'TransactionID', aggfunc = len)
    temp.reset_index(inplace = True)
    print(temp.head())
    for feature in fill_columns:
        print(f' filling-in {feature} Nulls')
        df[feature] = df.apply(
            lambda row: temp[feature][(temp[link_with] == row[link_with])].mode()[0] 
            if ((pd.isnull(row[feature])) and (len(temp[feature][(temp[link_with] == row[link_with])].mode().tolist()) !=0)) else row[feature],axis=1) 
    print(f"Count of NaN's in features after filling:")
    print(df[fill_columns].isnull().sum())
    return df

    In [22]:
    # Next we will use combination of card4, card6 values to triangulate possible missing values in other card columns
def crossfill_mode_2index(df, fill_columns, link_with):
    
    '''
    INPUT:
    df: dataframe where we are filling nulls
    fill_columns: columns of dataframe df, to fill the nulls
    link_with: '2 indexes used to check mode of columns (we are using 'card4 & 6 as pivot' in this case to determine mode of other columns )'
    
    RETURNs:
    df: dataframe after filling in possible nulls
    '''
    
    print(f"Count of total NaN's in selected features before filling:")
    print(df[fill_columns].isnull().sum())

    for feature in fill_columns:
        print(f'Filing-in {feature} Nulls')
        df[feature] = df.apply(
            lambda row: df[feature][(df[link_with[0]] == row[link_with[0]]) & (df[link_with[1]] == row[link_with[1]]) ].mode()[0] 
            if ((pd.isnull(row[feature])) and (len(df[feature][(df[link_with[0]] == row[link_with[0]]) & (df[link_with[1]] == row[link_with[1]]) ].mode()) !=0)) else row[feature],axis=1) 
    print(f"Count of NaN's in features after filling:")
    print(df[fill_columns].isnull().sum())
    return df

    (5.3.1) Starting with addr1, addr2 nulls:

    We know that addr1 identifies zipcode and addr2 identifies country of billing address While card in specific countries may be more susceptible to fraud due to local enforcement practices, zip code of billing address does not look like a suitable feature to influence fraud category

    we can check this by distribution of Frauds by different values of these features¶

    These are distances i.e. between merchant location zip code and billing zip code, and Ip address location zip code and billing zip code.¶

    Median values are being used to fill nulls as they are most fit to signify distance to learn to learn in our model.(also mode is not used as its a continuous variable, and mean is not used as it is suceptible to outliers)

    In [38]:
    # define a function to fill median values by checking from corresponding 'card1' records
def crossfill_median(df, fill_columns, link_with):
    
    '''
    INPUT:
    df: dataframe where we are filling nulls
    fill_columns: columns of dataframe df, to fill the nulls
    link_with: 'pivot_column used to check mode of columns (we are using 'card1' in this notebook )'
    
    RETURNs:
    df: dataframe after filling in possible nulls
    '''
    
    print(f"Count of NaN's in features before filling:")
    print(df[fill_columns].isnull().sum())
    

    for feature in fill_columns:
        print(f' filling-in {feature} Nulls')
        df[feature] = df.apply(
            lambda row: df[feature][(df[link_with] == row[link_with])].median() if (pd.isnull(row[feature]))  else row[feature],axis=1) 
    print(f"Count of NaN's in features after filling:")
    print(df[fill_columns].isnull().sum())
    return df
######
#Faster version using a prefilled pivot table
    
def crossfill_median2(df, list_index, fill_columns, link_with):
    
    print(f"Count of NaN's in features before filling:")
    print(df[fill_columns].isnull().sum())
    
    temp = df.pivot_table(index =list_index, values = fill_columns, aggfunc = np.median)
    temp.reset_index(inplace = True)
    print(temp.head())
    for feature in fill_columns:
        print(f' filling-in {feature} Nulls')
        df[feature] = df.apply(
            lambda row: temp[feature][(temp[link_with] == row[link_with])].median() if (pd.isnull(row[feature]))  else row[feature],axis=1) 
    print(f"Count of NaN's in features after filling:")
    print(df[fill_columns].isnull().sum())
    return df

    In [49]:
    ## Use this one for median 
def crossfill_median3(df, list_index, fill_columns, link_with):
    
    print(f"Count of NaN's in features before filling:")
    print(df[fill_columns].isnull().sum())
    
    temp = df.pivot_table(index =list_index, values = fill_columns, aggfunc = np.median)
    temp.reset_index(inplace = True)
    print(temp.head())
    for feature in fill_columns:
        print(f' filling-in {feature} Nulls')
        df[feature] = df.apply(
            lambda row: temp[feature][(temp[link_with] == row[link_with])].median() if (pd.isnull(row[feature]))  else row[feature],axis=1) 
    print(f"Count of NaN's in features after filling:")
    print(df[fill_columns].isnull().sum())
    return df

    # Function to get basic details about dataframe features
def get_value_counts(df, features):

    top5_values = {'feature_name':[],
                   'value1_name':[],'value1_count':[],
                   'value2_name':[],'value2_count':[],
                   'value3_name':[],'value3_count':[],
                   'value4_name':[],'value4_count':[],
                   'value5_name':[],'value5_count':[]
                  }
    for feature in features:
        
        values = df[feature].value_counts(dropna = False).nlargest(5).index.tolist()
        counts = df[feature].value_counts(dropna = False).nlargest(5).tolist()
        while len(values)<5:
            values.append('no_value')
            counts.append(0)

        top5_values['feature_name'].append(feature)
        top5_values['value1_name'].append(values[0])
        top5_values['value1_count'].append(counts[0])
        top5_values['value2_name'].append(values[1])
        top5_values['value2_count'].append(counts[1])
        top5_values['value3_name'].append(values[2])
        top5_values['value3_count'].append(counts[2])
        top5_values['value4_name'].append(values[3])
        top5_values['value4_count'].append(counts[3])
        top5_values['value5_name'].append(values[4])
        top5_values['value5_count'].append(counts[4])

    top5_value_counts = pd.DataFrame(top5_values)    
    return top5_value_counts

    from above analysis it seem safe to use below fill strategy¶

    (1) replacing nulls in V columns with mode for corresponsing card1 (mode is used as these are columns with most of the value counts hovering around few values only.) (2) fill balance nulls with mode of the columns

    However since (1) above is going to take hours for more than 300 features. we should have an efficient strategy. Lets check if card number/type makes any difference to the mode value. It was evident from above table that it does not. lets check once again

    In [74]:
    # make a list of features where highest value count among not nulls are covered by a single value
id_fill = {}
id90 = []
for feature in fill_columns:

    x = 100*df[feature].value_counts().nlargest(1)/(df.shape[0]-df[feature].isnull().sum())

    if x.iloc[0]>=90:
        print (f"{feature}:value '{x.index[0]}' covers {round(x.iloc[0], 2)}% not_nulls")
        new = {feature:x.index[0]}
        id_fill.update(new)
        id90.append(feature)
    # perhaps we can fill if % of highest value count is >90%
